<div id="review_2164282598" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2164282598" />
    <a title="Rachel Britt-busler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28857983-rachel-britt-busler"><img alt="Rachel Britt-busler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392844143p2/28857983.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2164282598?book_show_action=true">Oct 25, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rachel Britt-busler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rachel Britt-busler" href="/user/show/28857983-rachel-britt-busler">Rachel Britt-busler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2164282598&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2164282598" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7318289081217593214">I&apos;m giving this book 4 stars because I feel weird about books where it seems like I should be taking notes. This isn&apos;t so much a review as it is a collection of thoughts. So the big question I have is: what is this book about? Like what is the goal of the book?<br/><br/>The book puts you in the shoes of the first character (Stuart Gratton). You realize Jack Sawyer&apos;s narrative can&apos;t be trusted-but his brother Joe can be. Stuart initially meets Angela Sawyer. You&apos;ll want to remember these names as they&apos;re t</span>
  <span id="freeText7318289081217593214" style="display:none">I'm giving this book 4 stars because I feel weird about books where it seems like I should be taking notes. This isn't so much a review as it is a collection of thoughts. So the big question I have is: what is this book about? Like what is the goal of the book?<br /><br />The book puts you in the shoes of the first character (Stuart Gratton). You realize Jack Sawyer's narrative can't be trusted-but his brother Joe can be. Stuart initially meets Angela Sawyer. You'll want to remember these names as they're tied to each other. Later on, you learn both are the children of JL Sawyer. Which doesn't really seem possible. At the end of Jack's tail, he sees Brigit with a daughter named Angela. However, Joe has a vision where there's a son named Stuart. Both Jack and Joe though, hint that the children belong to Jack.<br /><br />This book feels like a puzzle but it also feels like work. A disappointing part of the book is Brigit. She's for the most part merely a prop to advance a story. She's just a beautiful girl. There's nothing defining about her. She feels hollow (but maybe this is a staple Priest thing-this can also be said of the girlfriend in The Prestige).<br /><br />The characters (save Stuart) all feel rather shallow. It's hard to feel anything for Jack or Joe. The realization that Churchill and Hess have doppelgangers seems underwhelming.<br /><br />Really though, this whole thought vomit of mine is just me saying I need to read this book a second time</span>
  <a data-text-id="7318289081217593214" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
