    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3428232032" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3428232032" />
    <a title="R. Andrew Lamonica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12033764-r-andrew-lamonica"><img alt="R. Andrew Lamonica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1345437370p2/12033764.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3428232032?book_show_action=true">Jul 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="R. Andrew Lamonica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="R. Andrew Lamonica" href="/user/show/12033764-r-andrew-lamonica">R. Andrew Lamonica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3428232032" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7750172133598356983">The Separation is a book that forces you to think. Are nations like people? If you abuse them, will they become abusers? If someone bloodied your nose, or the nose of your friend, would you bludgeon that person to death with a baseball bat? If not, should you support the escalation of a war where the nose-bloodying is proportionally-scaled-up to actual deaths?<br/><br/>Christopher Priest clearly wants you to think about these questions. But, he doesn&apos;t seem to be interested in promoting one set of answers</span>
  <span id="freeText7750172133598356983" style="display:none">The Separation is a book that forces you to think. Are nations like people? If you abuse them, will they become abusers? If someone bloodied your nose, or the nose of your friend, would you bludgeon that person to death with a baseball bat? If not, should you support the escalation of a war where the nose-bloodying is proportionally-scaled-up to actual deaths?<br /><br />Christopher Priest clearly wants you to think about these questions. But, he doesn't seem to be interested in promoting one set of answers over another. He puts forth a world where calmer heads prevailed in mid-WWII. But, doesn't make it sound like a paradise (or even an improvement) compared to the world we live in. Instead, the meat of the book focuses on some interpersonal relationships and on character development.<br /><br />I fear that this book may not have as long a shelf-life as it deserves. I consider myself well-educated, but I was only able to tell with certainty about 90% of the time which events were fictional and which were historical. I suspect that Mr. Priest's peers would be able to get to 99%. But, the average millennial might only be curtain about 60% and that means that they will miss out on some of the important implications (e.g. why the middle east is different in this alternative universe). <br /><br />Anyway, read this book. Check Wikipedia for dates and events to see how they went down in reality.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7750172133598356983" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

