<div id="review_1863834628" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1863834628" />
    <a title="Peter Walker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7844925-peter-walker"><img alt="Peter Walker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1460087931p2/7844925.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1863834628?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Peter Walker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Peter Walker" href="/user/show/7844925-peter-walker">Peter Walker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/25868696-the-separation">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1863834628" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10607318090167903300">This is the third book I&apos;ve read from Christopher Priest, and I&apos;m really coming to love his style: not only his writing style which is ethereal and opaque, vague and evasive, but his content which is both otherworldly and realistic. After two of his books I&apos;ve had a strong nostalgia for Haruki Murakami&apos;s &quot;Hard Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World.&quot; Both in tone and subject matter, Priest&apos;s work aligns well with some of Murakami, although the style and approach are quite different.<br/><br/>This book</span>
  <span id="freeText10607318090167903300" style="display:none">This is the third book I've read from Christopher Priest, and I'm really coming to love his style: not only his writing style which is ethereal and opaque, vague and evasive, but his content which is both otherworldly and realistic. After two of his books I've had a strong nostalgia for Haruki Murakami's "Hard Boiled Wonderland and the End of the World." Both in tone and subject matter, Priest's work aligns well with some of Murakami, although the style and approach are quite different.<br /><br />This book is a nuanced, tricky (for me) retelling of World War II - alternate history. What was convicting and embarrassing, as a reader, was realizing how many facts about the war I was ignorant or unclear on. I didn't know Rudolf Hess actually parachuted into Scotland with a peace deal for the British during the war. Nor did I know that Madagascar was a proposed location to "ship" Jews to get them out of Germany before the "Final Solution" was enacted (reminds me of Chabon's "Yiddish Police..." in Alaska, which was also based on an idea floated at the treaty). <br /><br />Enjoyable read with interesting, complicated characters and a captivating, alternative tie-in to real historical events.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10607318090167903300" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


