<span id="freeTextContainer8385046598196321134">4.49. An alternative history (or is it?) that asks more questions than it gives. My kind of book. It also provides convincing background to WWII history.<br/>Priest takes the psychological musings of The Affirmation together with a loosely similar structure to The Prestige (there&apos;s nothing wrong with a bit of formula - as other, more successful authors may tell you).<br/>One of the many hardships, I would imagine, of being at war is trying to live some sort of life through it. Priest paints a believable p</span>
  <span id="freeText8385046598196321134" style="display:none">4.49. An alternative history (or is it?) that asks more questions than it gives. My kind of book. It also provides convincing background to WWII history.<br />Priest takes the psychological musings of The Affirmation together with a loosely similar structure to The Prestige (there's nothing wrong with a bit of formula - as other, more successful authors may tell you).<br />One of the many hardships, I would imagine, of being at war is trying to live some sort of life through it. Priest paints a believable picture of the protagonists trying to do just that, together with the necessary description of the worse parts of armed conflict involving military and civilians.<br />Some of the topics explored may be harder for the more xenophobic of readers, but please try to keep an open mind.</span>
